@MAR1 - Well, there really is something called a RIP code, but it's related to the flow in and out of an inlet as the tide changes, and it is something that happens with every change of the tide. It's the same thing as a tidal current, which is a better name for it. 

What most people erroneously call a RIP tide is really a current that forms when the water that rushes up a beach from the waves has to return, and for reasons of local topography and/or the directions from which the waves are coming, get channeled into a distinct current at one spot along the shore. They are not associated with an inlet and are not caused by the tides. Although tidal currents can be stronger, their location and timing are known and are probably not a danger to most people aware of them. But people "from away" might get caught in them and they could, therefore be categorized as "dangerous." 

Rip current, on the other hand, can form unexpectedly and without warning, where people are swimming, so they present a danger to the people there.

